etymologies: mid 17th century; earliest use found in William Foster (b. 1591), Church of England clergyman and writer. From stick + lac

definitions: Lac in its natural form as secreted by a lac insect (family Kerriidae) and encrusted on twigs.

notes.text: Sticklac is removed from the twigs and processed into pellets called seedlac. Seedlac is further purified into solid or liquid shellac.
